"Glad to see you sir: hope we shall often have that pleasure in future," said
                     Mr. Smith with great appearance of cordiality for one of his reserved demeanor;
                     but to the Southerner his manner seemed barely civil.

"That is very true," replied our hero, a little shaken in his determination,
                     for he was fond of society, and as he intended remaining some time in the city,
                     he was naturally desirous of forming eligible acquaintances.

"This, surely, must be the abode of my Peri," thought the enraptured youth;
                     "and those beautiful animals are her playful companions. She betrays the
                     tenderness of her heart even in her love for the brute creation."

"Children," said he, in a strong voice, addressing the newly married couple;
                     "children, kneel; for, with one foot in the grave I send you my last blessing,
                     and the blessing of a dying man is sacred."

And as this cargo was composed entirely of coffee, rice and tea, the result was
                     that Captain Pamphile had no occasion to stop at either Mocha, Bombay or Pekin;
                     which was a great saving to him in time and money.
